    body: "Pope Leo XIII's encyclical Rerum Novarum ('Of New Things'), issued on May 15, 1891, was the Catholic Church's first systematic response to the social upheaval of the Industrial Revolution. It affirmed workers' right to just wages, reasonable working hours, and safe conditions, while defending private property against socialist collectivism. It also endorsed workers' right to form unions and called on the state to protect the vulnerable. The encyclical launched a tradition of social teaching that every subsequent pope has continued.",
    example: "Rerum Novarum directly inspired the formation of Catholic labor unions, cooperative movements, and political parties across Europe and Latin America. In the United States, it emboldened Monsignor John A. Ryan, who drafted the 'Bishops' Program of Social Reconstruction' in 1919 — a document that anticipated many New Deal policies. Every decade since 1891 has seen a major papal social encyclical building on Leo XIII's foundation.",
