    body: "The Great Western Schism began in 1378 when the cardinals who had elected Pope Urban VI, dissatisfied with his erratic behavior, elected a rival pope, Clement VII, who returned to Avignon. For nearly forty years, Christendom was divided between Roman and Avignonese obediences, with saints and scholars on both sides. The crisis deepened in 1409 when the Council of Pisa elected a third pope. The schism was finally resolved at the Council of Constance (1414-1418), which deposed the rival claimants and elected Pope Martin V.",
    example: "The absurdity of three simultaneous popes led to the rise of conciliarism — the theory that a general council holds supreme authority over the pope. The Council of Constance issued the decree Haec Sancta (1415), claiming conciliar supremacy, though this was later rejected. Remarkably, saints like Catherine of Siena and Vincent Ferrer supported different claimants, proving that even the holiest Christians could not discern which pope was legitimate.",
