    body: "The Investiture Controversy (1076-1122) was a conflict between the papacy and the Holy Roman Empire over the appointment of bishops and abbots. The practice of lay investiture — whereby secular rulers conferred the ring and staff of episcopal office — had become deeply entrenched as emperors used bishops as administrative officers. Pope Gregory VII's reforms, especially his decree Dictatus Papae (1075), directly challenged this system. The controversy was resolved by the Concordat of Worms (1122), which distinguished between the spiritual and temporal aspects of episcopal office.",
